<TEXT>
a scientist is planning to use nazi studies 
of concentration camp prisoners deliberately frozen to death to 
further his research about hypothermia 
but some scientists and jewish leaders have sharply criticized 
his intention to use data obtained during the holocaust 
dr robert pozos director of the hypothermia research 
laboratory at the university of minnesota duluth says he plans to 
analyze and republish the treatment of shock from prolonged 
exposure to cold a study by doctors at dachau it includes 
observation and physiological measurements of people placed in vats 
of freezing liquid often to the point of death according to those 
familiar with the study 
we should under no circumstances use the information it was 
gained in an immoral way said dr daniel callahan director of 
the hastings center a medical ethics think tank in briarcliff 
manor ny 
i think it goes to legitimizing the evil done i think the 
findings are tainted by the horror and misery said abraham h 
foxman national director of the antidefamation league 
because mammals differ widely in their physiological response to 
cold hypothermia research is uniquely dependent on human test 
subjects says pozos a specialist in the field for 12 years 
it could advance my work in that it takes human subjects 
farther than were willing he said 
several medical ethicists contend study of the nazi research 
could save lives and if published with a condemnation of the 
methods call attention to the plight of the jews poles and 
gypsies killed in the experiments 
because the egyptians used slave labor does that mean we 
should never gaze at the pyramids asked dr thomas murray 
director of the center for biomedical ethics at case western 
reserve university in cleveland 
it sends a chill down every normal human beings spine to 
think of the horrible things the nazis did there but im 
separating the results and the circumstances said ephraim 
zuroff israeli representative to the simon wiesenthal center in 
los angeles actually if the us doctor dedicated his study to 
the memory of those victims of the nazis it would serve as a nice 
way of reminding people about the horrible experiments 
use of nazi science by postworld war ii researchers is rare but 
not unprecedented after facing a similar quandary this year the 
federal environmental protection agency deleted references to nazi 
research in its own draft report on a toxic gas 
pozos 45 says he decided to use the nazi hypothermia data 
after seeing a resurgence of public and scientific curiosity about 
it he says copies of a 1945 english translation of the dachau 
study have been available in about a dozen libraries around the 
country 
motivated in part by the loss of pilots in the frigid north sea 
the germans used 100 to 300 prisoners to test the bodys response 
to extreme cold pozos said how many died is unclear besides 
testing the phenomenon of freezing the doctors experimented with 
warming techniques ranging from bodytobody contact to alcohol 
ingestion pozos said 
word of pozos plans for the old nazi experiments spread after 
he contacted university of minnesota medical ethicist arthur caplan 
for advice caplan wrote a newspaper column about the issue 
pozos said he has had a generally positive response including 
calls from about a halfdozen holocaust survivors they said i 
should get something out of this so these people would not have 
died in vain said pozos 
within two months pozos said he hopes to republish the german 
study in a scientific journal with his own analysis of its quality 
and application to modern hypothermia research 
while calling the study a record of unimaginable horror and 
cruelty caplan said he believes pozos should be allowed to 
republish it under strict guidelines among other stipulations 
caplan urges omission of the nazi doctors names to ensure no 
credit is conferred 
if the data can prevent a single death then it is worth 
tolerating the stench of past deaths that will cling to each 
page caplan wrote 
caplan has organized an international symposium on nazi science 
tentatively scheduled for may 1989 at the university of minnesota 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

