<TEXT>
a top department of energy official conceded 
wednesday that two whistleblowers from washington state may have 
been harassed by their superiors after testifying last year before 
a house subcommittee about safety problems at the hanford nuclear 
reservation 
under secretary of energy joseph salgado who has responsibility 
for the department of energys safety programs at facilities such 
as the hanford reservation said that both he and the department 
had failed to protect casey ruud and james simkin from any 
retaliation by their employer 
it was negligent on my part salgado told the oversight and 
investigations subcommittee of the house energy committee 
salgado said the handling of ruud and simpkin called into 
question the departments efforts to improve its safety programs 
and that the two should have been praised rather than harassed 
we failed to acknowledge what they had done said salgado 
it was the wrong thing to do 
salgado also said that doe had sent the wrong message to 
employees who are concerned about safety at federal nuclear 
facilities 
during an october hearing before the same subcommittee ruud and 
simkin had outlined a series of safety problems at the central 
washington nuclear facility and salgado had pledged they they would 
not suffer because of their testimony 
ruud and simpkin said wednesday they had been harassed and 
intimidated since their last appearance before the subcommittee 
and that other workers at the hanford reservation are afraid to 
report safety problems for fear of reprisals 
ruud laid off in february by the westinghouse hanford co said 
he was told by his superiors there was an unwritten 
understanding that he would never be promoted 
in addition ruud said one supervisor roger johnson who now 
heads one of westinghouses employee concerns committee told him 
if his testimony before the subcommittee prevented him from getting 
anotherjob thats just too bad 
william jacobi president of westinghouse hanford admitted that 
johnson heads the employee concerns committee but said he was not 
aware of ruuds allegation prior to wednesday and promised to 
investigate ruuds claims 
there are many other people at hanford who are afraid to 
come forward with serious problems because they fear reprisals 
ruud testified 
simpkin still works at the hanford reservation but said he has 
been transferred to a department where he cannot contribute 
to correcting the safety problems at hanford 
less than a month after last falls hearing simpkin said he 
received a letter of reprimand from his supervisor the letter was 
withdrawn after an energy department investigation found it was 
unfair and unjustified 
some republican members of the committee suggested that perhaps 
simpkin and ruud were not qualified for the transfers they had 
sought 
others suggested the two hadnt been singled out but had been 
caught up in the massive layoffs and employee reshuffling resulting 
from the closing of the reactor and the decision not to locate the 
nations first highlevel nuclear waste dump at hanford 
no congressional committee can function if witnesses have 
apprehensions about what will happen if they tell the truth said 
rep john dingel dmich subcomittee chairman the matter will 
not end with this meeting today 
but the function of this hearing was not to demean you or your 
department dingell told salgado 
