<TEXT>
donald t regan took time off from discussing 
his book on the inner workings of president reagans white house to 
tell congress that financial markets and the government must act 
quickly to reassure the nations investors 
the former treasury secretary said wednesday that there should 
have been more prompt action after last octobers stock market 
crash this thing happened over seven months ago he said 
regan told the senate banking committee that a form of 
computerized trading called index arbitrage should be prohibited 
and that all transactions involving stock index futures should be 
temporarily halted both practices he said make the markets 
excessively volatile and have scared worried individual investors 
off 
a stock market whose main participants are speculators and 
their programs cannot be a healthy market and an unhealthy wall 
street will sooner or later drag down the real economy said 
regan the former chief executive officer of merrill lynch amp co 
the banking panel has been holding hearings on the dramatic 
price swings that have dominated the markets since oct 19 when 
the dow jones industrial average fell a record 508 points 
regan who was white house chief of staff for two years after 
being treasury secretary has spent most of his time recently 
talking about his new book for the record from wall street to 
washington in it he says first lady nancy reagan often consults 
astrologers when planning the presidents schedule and making other 
decisions 
regan declined to discuss his book wednesday with reporters 
but he did blame computerdriven trading especially index 
arbitrage for the markets problems 
traders conducting index arbitrage use computers to profit from 
price discrepancies between the stock and futures markets by 
simultaneously buying in one market and selling in the other 
in my mind we should start by banning index option arbitrage 
and then proceed with other reforms which will restore public 
confidence in the financial markets regan said 
he said problems also have been caused by stock futures which 
are traded in chicago in a stock index futures transaction an 
amount of cash equal to the value of a collection of stocks changes 
hands with an agreement that the portfolio will be bought back at 
whatever those stocks values are at a specific future date 
opponents of the practice say the massive amounts of money 
involved add unpredictability to the stock market when traders buy 
or sell equities to protect their futures transactions 
i think there should be a pause in index futures trading 
regan told reporters after his testimony it wont hurt very much 
for a threemonth or sixmonth pause here while we take a look at 
the instrument itself and how its used to see whether or not it 
should be permitted to continue 
regan told the senators the nations financial markets or the 
federal agencies that regulate them should initiate the steps he 
recommended if not congress should act he said 
at the same hearing george l ball chairman and chief 
executive officer of prudentialbache securities inc said the 
abolition of stock index futures should be considered 
most knowledgeable professionals agree that if it were not for 
index futures stock market moves would be far less wild sudden or 
irrationally large he said 
charles r schwab who owns the discount brokerage firm that 
bears his name also told the lawmakers that program trading should 
be abolished if other steps to restore market confidence dont work 
in surveys we have conducted we hear over and over again the 
theme that individual investors fear they cannot compete in markets 
that are so dominated by the volatility introduced by program 
trading and index arbitrage he said 
earlier leo melamed chairman of the executive committee of the 
board of governors of the chicago mercantile exchange told 
reporters that index arbitrage helps stabilize the markets by 
ensuring that stock and futures prices closely track each other 
im not going to defend perception he said the reality 
is it is not a factor in the volatility 
</TEXT>
