<TEXT>
the following are biographical sketches of the 
four british traitors recruited at cambridge university in the 
1930s by a soviet agent who is still unidentified 
harold adrian russell kim philby was regarded as the most 
damaging spy to western intelligence the only one of the cambridge 
spy ring who was not a homosexual he is believed to have become a 
soviet agent in 1933 the year in which he saw fascists fighting 
communists and labor unionists in austria when entrusted with the 
russian desk of mi6 the british intelligence unit that controls 
agents abroad he told the soviets who was spying on them he 
served in washington as liaison officer with the cia he betrayed a 
britishus plan to land guerrillas in communist albania in 1946 
and 300 were killed he fled to moscow in 1963 while working as 
journalist in beirut 
anthony frederick blunt an art historian recruited spies for 
moscow during the 1930s he spied for the soviets during world war 
ii while working for the british mi5 counterespionage service he 
was unmasked in 1964 but was granted immunity in return for telling 
all he knew about soviet intelligence he was publicly exposed in 
1979 and stripped of the knighthood conferred for his services as 
royal art adviser he died in london of a heart attack in 1983 
guy francis de moncy burgess became a soviet agent in the 
1930s because he believed only soviet dictator joseph stalin could 
stop adolf hitler he worked as a british diplomat in washington 
and looked after far east affairs during the korean war he lived 
in washington with philby who was also working for the british 
foreign office he died in moscow in 1963 at age 52 
donald duart maclean worked for the foreign office and was 
posted to washington in 1944 but recalled because of heavy 
drinking he worked with americans and canadians on the combined 
policy committee for joint atomic development and gave the soviets 
documents on nuclear planning it is believed he and philby gave 
atomic bomb secrets to stalin maclean fled to moscow with burgess 
in may 1951 where he was given the kgb rank of colonel he died in 
moscow in 1983 at age 69 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

