<TEXT>
a hormone that causes the body to produce 
immune cells is in the final stages of clinical testing and may 
provide a breakthrough in protecting the elderly against death from 
influenza and pneumonia two researchers say 
this may well be a research breakthrough for the treatment of 
disease among elderly people dr william b ershler of the 
university of wisconsin told the senate committee on aging 
the committee is conducting a hearing on research into the 
health problems of the elderly 
thymosin alpha one a form of the hormone thymosin has now been 
given to elderly patients in two early clinical trials and in both 
cases the level of immune action was increased ershler said 
wednesday 
flu vaccine generally is effective in only about 25 percent of 
the elderly who receive it he said but in studies using thymosin 
alpha one the effectiveness was increased to 70 percent 
researchers have long known that the immune system becomes 
increasingly weaker as people age he said as a result 
infections remain a major cause of morbidity and mortality in 
elderly people he said 
ershler said a deficiency of one of the immune cells called 
tcell lymphocyte is caused by a decline in the function of the 
thymus gland this in turn has been traced to a shortage of 
thymosin 
an expanded study using 400 patients at the us soldiers and 
airmens home here was conducted last fall and winter results 
have not been analyzed said ershler but it may be a research 
breakthrough 
allan l goldstein a professor at george washington university 
and a codiscoverer of thymosin said the washington study has 
great promise 
it is hoped that within two years well be able to apply this 
new approach to lower the incidence of flu and pneumonia among the 
elderly goldstein told the committee 
he said influenza affects millions of elderly americans 
annually costs hundreds of millions of dollars in medical care and 
causes about 25000 deaths among people over age 65 
