<TEXT>
researchers say they are encouraged by 
experimental use of a derivative of cows milk to prevent 
travelers diarrhea and hope to test their discovery on people 
going to developing countries 
in a report today they said that powdered concentrations of 
milk antibodies appeared to protect people from the effects of e 
coli bacteria a common cause of diarrhea 
these preliminary results are highly encouraging they wrote 
in the new england journal of medicine 
the researchers led by dr carol o tacket of the university of 
maryland school of medicine found that the treatment may provide 
an alternative to prescription antibiotics and overthecounter 
bismuth subsalicylate which can keep people from getting diarrhea 
the researchers said that about half of all travelers to 
developing countries get diarrhea 
we want to do a field study to see if it works among 
travelers said tacket our study was a very artificial 
situation 
to make the concentrate cows were first vaccinated with 
varieties of e coli that cause diarrhea the cows then produced 
antibodies in their milk that protected them from these microbes 
the researchers removed these antibodies and prepared them in 
powder form 
ten volunteers drank the powdered e coli antibodies dissolved 
in water three times a day for three days ten others got other 
forms of antibodies 
then all were given diarrheacausing e coli none of the 10 who 
got the e coli antibodies developed diarrhea however nine of the 
10 in the comparison group got the illness 
