<TEXT>
the national institutes of health will stop 
funding artificial heart research and will focus instead on smaller 
devices intended to assist rather than replace hearts according to 
a report published today 
while the artificial heart device seemed to work well the 
biology didnt work said dr claude lenfant director of the 
national heart lung and blood institute 
the human body just couldnt seem to tolerate it we were left 
wondering whether the idea of a permanent replacement will ever 
work lenfant said in an interview published in the atlanta 
constitution and the atlanta journal 
the decision means four institutions awarded contracts last year 
for artificial heart research will receive only about 1 million of 
the 5 million each was expecting over the next five years 
this is a tremendous setback for scientific advancement in the 
field said dr donald olsen head of artificial heart research 
at the university of utah which had received one of the contracts 
he said the decision will set back development of a permanent 
artificial heart for more than 10 years 
this does not mean the end of the artificial heart program it 
means we are taking a different approach it may take somewhat 
longer but it may also help us develop a device that works 
better lenfant said 
barney clark became the first recipient of an artificial heart 
dec 2 1982 in surgery performed at the university of utah by dr 
william devries he died the following march 
four other patients have received permanent artificial hearts 
three at humanaaudubon hospital in louisville ky where devries 
now works and one in stockholm sweden william schroeder was the 
longest survivor living almost two years with the jarvik7 
artificial heart 
all of the patients however suffered severe complications 
including strokes and major infections 
lenfant said reports about those problems were one reason the 
government decided to withdraw support for continued development 
instead the agency will focus its funding on smaller 
ventricular assist devices as stopgap measures for patients 
awaiting a transplanted human heart he said 
we believe it is time to try them in patients who need 
longterm support lenfant said 
so far such bridge devices have been been used only for a 
few weeks lenfant said the government wants to see if they will 
work for three or four years at a time 
the newspapers said the nih decision would be officially 
announced next week 
