forest service officials asked congress today 
for hot pursuit authority against heavily armed marijuana 
growers who forced the closure of 886000 acres of national forest 
land last year as unsafe for tourists and timber interests 
deputy forest service chief william l rice told a senate 
hearing that his 150 law enforcement agents need statutory 
authority to pursue fleeing marijuana farmers beyond the boundaries 
of national forests and grasslands especially in the far west 
where the problem is most acute 
his request was endorsed by sens tom harkin diowa and wyche 
fowler dga who said these marijuana gardens are protected by 
a marquis de sade torture chamber of devices intended to maim 
cripple or kill intruders 
rep ron wyden dore testifying at a senate agriculture 
subcommittee hearing said illicit marijuana cultivation is a 
problem of staggering proportions in the west 
wyden is chief sponsor of a bill that would grant forest service 
agents authority to conduct investigations searches seizures and 
arrests outside the boundaries of national forests if drug crimes 
originate there 
he said the agents are hamstrung under current law because 
they are authorized to go after these criminals but only as long 
as they remain within the boundaries of the federal forests 
wyden also proposed to stiffen federal penalties for 
unauthorized use of chemical herbicides and fertilizers in national 
forests and to increase the maximum penalties for marijuana 
cultivation on those lands which total 191 million acres in 44 
states puerto rico and the virgin islands 
frank g packwood a special agent in the trinityshasta 
national forest in california blamed the lack of hot pursuit 
authority on the poor success rate in prosecuting marijuana 
growers who have an estimated 14 billion in annual profits 
in 1986 packwood said 70 percent of californias 872 arrests 
for illegal marijuana farming went unprosecuted because of hampered 
investigations 
law enforcement has failed to establish a deterrent to 
cultivation activity and has become in the eyes of the grower just 
another business expense packwood said 
the subcommittee chaired by harkins heard testimony that 
marijuana growers are using a wide variety of sophisticated weapons 
to guard their farming plots in national forests including attack 
dogs who get their commands from radios mounted on their collars 
