interim rule primarily concerns future natural disasters in the 
national forests 
however he said the agency also needs to speed up appeal 
procedures for recovery and rehabilitation activities that resulted 
from 1987s severe fire season in california and oregon it was 
this natural disaster that brought to our attention the need for 
special appeal procedures 
under the interim rule adopted today anyone may appeal 
decisions on recovery and rehabilitation activities that result 
from natural disasters such as wildfires flooding earthquakes 
and high winds he said 
those who appeal will be entitled to a onelevel appeal 
process which must be completed within 90 days robertson said 
previously appeal processes could be reviewed at two 
administrative levels 
an estimated 22 billion board feet of national forest timber 
were destroyed or damaged in california and oregon in the 1987 fire 
season with about 40 percent of that volume offered for sale he 
said 
