<TEXT>
harold kim philby is dead but the bitter 
aftertaste of his colossal betrayal still lingers in britain 
even 25 years after the privileged english gentleman was 
unmasked as moscows highestplaced mole in western intelligence 
central questions remain unanswered 
were there others of higher rank were the operations of western 
intelligence agencies compromised more seriously than they realize 
when philby gave his only interview to a western journalist four 
months before he died was it part of a new plot by his kgb masters 
to discredit the british and undermine their relationship with 
washington 
a tribute to philby came thursday the day after he died at age 
76 from peter wright a former british intelligence officer 
wright has done much to keep the scandal alive with his 
allegation that an even higher mole existed the late sir roger 
hollis who directed the mi5 security service from 1956 to 1965 
wrights claim is in his volume of memoirs called spycatcher 
which is banned in britain 
in a statement from australia where he now lives wright called 
philby an outstanding man in the intelligence world 
philby became a soviet agent while at cambridge university in 
the 1930s joined the secret service and rose to high rank he was 
believed to be in line to head mi6 the sister service of mi5 
his network unraveled in 1951 with the defection of guy burgess 
and donald maclean to moscow but philby escaped exposure for 12 
more years in 1963 he too defected 
in 1964 the fourth man anthony blunt confessed he had 
worked for the soviets while in mi5 and received immunity in 
exchange for information about the other three his treason was 
kept secret and he eventually became art adviser to queen elizabeth 
ii receiving a knighthood 
blunts past was made public in 1979 and he was stripped of his 
honors he died in london in 1983 
the damage to british security which shared secrets with 
washington is incalculable now that all four of stalins 
englishmen finally are dead the suspicion persists that there 
were five 
wrights claim about hollis whether true or not illustrates 
the doubt that still eats at the british security services because 
of philbys treachery 
its bad for morale and its actually bad for operations 
said rupert allason a conservative member of parliament and who 
writes histories and analyses of espionage under the name nigel 
west 
he said the suspicions mean intelligence analysts must ask 
themselves constantly whether the files they use contain tainted 
information left by the traitors 
philby still was a kgb officer when he died and intelligence 
