<TEXT>
the first decline in an annual index of 
american health practices illustrates there is a big difference 
between people knowing they should eat right and exercise and 
actually doing it authorities said thursday 
dr james michael mcginnis a federal health official said the 
drop underscores the need for leaders to redouble our efforts to 
convince americans that health promotion ideas are not a fad 
despite extensive publicity in recent years about the value of 
proper diet and exercise the 1988 survey by prevention magazine 
showed few gains in those areas mcginnis director of the office 
of disease prevention and health promotion noted 
in particular he told reporters it is an issue of some 
concern that we havent seen improvement in the number of people 
who told pollsters they try a lot to avoid eating too much fat 
only 54 percent answered yes to that question down from 56 
percent in the 1987 report the latest result also is down from the 
55 percent who gave a yes response in polling done for the 
initial index in 1984 
the overall 1988 prevention index stood at 648 out of a 
possible 100 down from 652 last year but 33 points above the 
first index in 1984 
however the overall gain from 1984 is due largely to sharp 
jumps in the number of people who have smoke detectors in their 
homes a 15 percent jump and the number who report wearing auto 
seatbelts a 38 percent climb 
mcginnis complimented the commercial magazine for compiling the 
index noting that is the only survey that has tracked trends in 21 
specific areas over a fiveyear period 
one clear message from this years survey is that the spread 
of good health habits is not automatic said thomas dybdahl 
director of the prevention index 
people may know more than ever about good health but they may 
not be acting on what they know in key areas such as diet 
exercise and weight control there is still much room for 
improvement 
for example the number saying they are making efforts to limit 
highcholesterol foods fell from 46 percent in the 1987 report to 
42 percent this year the same as it was in 1984 
compared with 1984 there was a twopercentagepoint drop in the 
number who said they try to avoid too many sweets and threepoint 
decline in the number who said they get seven or eight hours sleep 
most nights 
although up two points from the 1984 report only 35 percent of 
americans say they exercise strenuously three or more days a week 
and only 24 percent say they are at their proper weight up one 
point from 1984 
seventytwo percent say they do not smoke the same as last year 
and up two points from 1984 
humphrey taylor president of louis harris and associates which 
conducts the poll that forms the basis for the index described the 
figures on diet and nutrition as amazingly flat from a 
statistical viewpoint 
taylor said the lack of significant improvement in the diet and 
exercise portions of the fiveyear survey show a gap between lip 
service and good intentions and actual practice 
weight control is a truly dismal story he said noting that 
76 percent of americans think they are overweight we remain the 
most obese country in the world he said 
harris pollsters ask the same questions each year to give an 
accurate yeartoyear comparison 
the current years report was based on telephone interviews 
conducted with 1250 randomly selected adults nov 1125 and has a 
3 percent margin of error 
taylor acknowledged that the typically small yeartoyear 
changes registered in the survey often fall within the margin of 
error 
however he said the theoretical chance for error is largely 
overriden because consistent trends tracked over the fiveyear 
sampling period give added credence to the figures reported in any 
one year 
the singlenumber prevention index itself is derived by 
assigning weights to each of the 21 survey questions and applying 
poll results to that relative value scale 
for example not smoking is assigned the highest ranking 978 
on a scale of one to 10 
