a truce ordered by syria and iran ended a 
sixday battle between rival militias thursday in which the radical 
hezbollah captured most of south beiruts shiite moslem slums 
sniper fire was heard in the ramshackle 16 square miles adjacent 
to the beirut airport but the howitzers and tank cannons were 
silent police reported a woman killed and two other civilians 
wounded in the ghobeiri neighborhood 
police said 188 people were killed and 534 wounded in the battle 
that began last friday between the mainstream amal militia backed 
by syria and hezbollah or party of god which is loyal to iran 
south of the capital the israeli air force blasted palestinian 
bases in its eighth raid into lebanon this year police said six 
fighterbombers made three passes to rocket targets near barja 16 
miles from beirut there were no reports of deaths or serious 
injuries 
the truce was ordered for 11 pm wednesday after telephone 
conversations between president hafez assad of syria and president 
ali khamenei of iran 
sheik mohammed hussein fadlallah spiritual leader of hezbollah 
said he had no information about the 18 foreign hostages in 
lebanon most of whom are believed held in the slums by groups 
linked to hezbollah there has been no word of the foreigners who 
include nine americans since the fighting began 
although its fighting force was outnumbered 21 hezbollah 
appeared to have won the contest for supremacy police said it 
controlled 70 percent of the slums when the fighting ended 
compared with about onethird when it began 
police estimated hezbollahs fighting force at 3000 men they 
said amal put about 6500 men into the field about 2000 brought 
in from the syriancontrolled bekaa valley in east lebanon 
syria has 25000 soldiers in lebanon and sent 7500 of them to 
moslem west beirut in february 1987 to stop factional war although 
they patrol west beirut the syrians have not entered the southern 
shiite slums 
after 13 years of civil war assad was the undisputed power 
broker in lebanon until iran began challenging syrian influence 
among the 12 million shiites the countrys largest sect 
