<DOCNO> AP880512-0163 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
depressed teenagers intent on killing 
themselves show chemical abnormalities in their brains that appear 
to predispose them to suicide according to a study released 
thursday 
it clearly demonstrates some brain differences in suicidal 
adolescents its not purely a mind phenomenon said dr neal d 
ryan assistant professor of psychiatry at the university of 
pittsburgh 
earlier studies have found similar abnormalities in the brains 
of suicidal adults although experts are divided as to what 
conclusions can be drawn ryans research is believed to be the 
first that demonstrates neurochemical abnormalities in suicidal 
adolescents 
what this suggests is that there is a biochemical basis to at 
least depressive people with chronic suicidal plans ryan said 
theres something that goes on with the brain and there are 
environmental phenomena that impinge on that 
ryan said his findings reported at the american psychiatric 
associations annual conference in montreal could help doctors 
identify and treat certain patients before they try to commit 
suicide 
irma lann a science administrator in child and adolescent 
disorders research for the national institute of mental health 
said ryans work is preliminary and further study is needed 
its premature to even think that we could be able to identify 
groups of suicidal adolescents she said 
of the 29453 suicides in the united states in 1985 the last 
year for which figures are available 2127 were committed by 
youngsters 19 and under according to the national center for 
health statistics about 80 percent of them were boys 
boys and girls are afflicted about equally by depression but 
while more girls attempt suicide more boys succeed at it 
according to ryan 
ryan and dr joaquim puigantich professor of psychiatry at 
pitt began their study in 1980 at the new york state psychiatric 
institute in new york city they continued their work funded by 
the national institute of mental health after moving in 1984 to 
western psychiatric institute and clinic in pittsburgh 
from 1980 to 1987 the psychiatrists monitored the growth 
hormone secretion of 140 boys and girls ranging in age from 12 to 
just under 18 the tests were conducted while the subjects slept 
most growth hormone secretion occurs during sleep especially 
during the first several hours according to ryan at least three 
neurotransmitter systems in the brain are involved in controlling 
sleep growth hormone secretion which also affects moods 
the 34 youngsters who suffered from major depression and had 
attempted suicide or devised a suicide plan secreted less growth 
hormone than the 40 depressed but nonsuicidal students and 66 
healthy children whose levels were about the same ryan said the 
subjects sex was not a factor and their ages were taken into 
account 
later 43 of the students received a onetime shot of 
desipramine an antidepressant known to stimulate the release of 
growth hormone 
among the eight depressed suicidal youths who received the 
shot less growth hormone was released than among the 12 depressed 
but nonsuicidal and 23 healthy adolescents ryan said 
</TEXT>
