<TEXT>
conrail crew members in a fatal train accident 
suffered from a lack of sleep and could have dozed off while still 
instinctively performing basic duties an industrial psychologist 
testified thursday 
donald i tepas professor of psychology and director of the 
industrial and organizational psychology program at the university 
of connecticut said the three crew members on each of the two 
trains suffered from chronic sleep deprivation 
tepas testified during the second day of a national 
transportation safety board hearing on the jan 14 train accident 
in thompsontown which killed four people 
the two conrail trains one hauling coal and the other carrying 
trailervans smashed headon at about 8 am killing the engineer 
and the brakeman on both trains and derailing all five locomotives 
damage was estimated at 5 million 
tepas said the rail employees erratic work schedules harsh 
monotonous work environment and a lack of programs to help 
employees deal with job stress promote sleeping on the job 
work systems which result in night work shifts of unusual 
length and unpredictable work hours result in conditions which 
place workers and the general public at risk he said in prepared 
testmony 
spokesmen for conrail a private freight rail organization set 
up by congress to operate six bankrupt railroads have said they 
wouldnt comment on any of the testimony 
during his testimony tepas said workers on erratic schedules do 
not make up for lost sleep nor do they adapt to those schedules 
the same workers are not usually able to judge how their work has 
been affected while suffering from chronic sleep deprivation he 
added 
though asleep people can still react automatically in different 
situations he said adding that dozing rail workers could respond 
to danger signals as part of a natural reflex 
in all stages of sleep it is possible for people to perform 
simple responses to simple stimuli tepas said 
people can sleep for a few seconds or minutes and can perform 
quite well when they wake up he added 
us railroad companies must pay more attention to the 
consequences of sleep deprivation tepas said 
training employees who work unpredictable work schedules how to 
handle odd sleeping hours would help as well as adding some kind 
of change to routine duties he said 
the accident apparently occurred when the westbound trailer 
train had been shifted to an eastbound track on the conrail main 
line between harrisburg and pittsburgh the eastbound coal train 
apparently ran a stop signal and smashed headon into the trailer 
train 
the two survivors of the accident both said wednesday they had 
had only a few hours of sleep before they reported to duty the day 
of the wreck 
