<TEXT>
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan on 
thursday urged the house to follow the senates lead and pass major 
legislation to give banks new securities underwriting powers 
greenspan said the federal reserve favored the approach taken by 
the senate which in late march approved legislation that would 
repeal most restrictions of the depressionera glasssteagall act 
that statute barred a mingling of the banking and securities 
industries 
the 1933 law was one of the reforms passed following the 1929 
stock market crash it was aimed at curbing the types of 
speculation which were blamed for the crash 
greenspan said that one of the attractive features of the senate 
legislation is that its nearcomplete repeal of the 
glasssteagall act allows for a market driven evolution of 
financial services and products 
i would urge the house in its deliberations in the months 
ahead to adopt an approach similar to that of the senate 
greenspan said 
however the senate proposal sponsored by sen william 
proxmire dwis faces an uncertain future opponents of the 
measure in the securities industry have an ally in rep fernand st 
germain dri chairman of the house banking committee 
once before in 1984 the senate passed a bill to give banks 
broader powers but the house has never done so 
greenspan made his comments in a speech to banking officials in 
chicago his remarks were also released in washington 
greenspan said the legislation did not represent a bailout for 
banks but was instead a reorganization of the financial services 
industry which would better serve the public 
the public benefits of expanded powers include not only a 
stronger and safer banking system but also the more efficient and 
convenient delivery of a wider array of lowercost financial 
services he said 
the senate bill would permit a company that owns a bank to also 
own a securities company as long as the two subsidiaries were 
operated separately the securities affiliate would be allowed to 
underwrite municipalrevenue bonds mortgagebacked securities and 
commercial paper within six months of the bill becoming law the 
legislation would allow the securities affiliates to begin 
underwriting mutual funds and corporate bonds 
in 1991 the legislation requires that congress vote on whether 
to allow the securities affiliates to take the next step of being 
able to underwrite corporate stock 
</TEXT>
