<TEXT>
the soviet union is turning increasingly to 
barter arrangements with other countries in an effort to stretch 
its declining reserves of foreign currency an agriculture 
department analyst said thursday 
foreign currency is tight for the soviet government which in 
turn has decreased the soviet unions buying power significantly 
said thomas hamby of the departments foreign agricultural service 
hamby now the agencys deputy director of marketing for dairy 
livestock and poultry recently returned from moscow after 2 years 
as us agricultural attache his remarks were in a new issue of 
the agencys foreign agriculture magazine 
the soviets make it plain they are in a better position to 
exchange products for foreign goods than to pay in foreign currency 
this is a difficult constraint on trade from the us 
standpoint hamby said the soviet union simply does not have the 
ability to supply the quantity or quality of either agricultural or 
nonagricultural products which would make a barter arrangement 
feasible 
hamby said the united states imports only about 25 million 
worth of soviet agricultural products each year while the soviet 
unions imports of us farm products averages around 2 billion 
annually 
this situation has led to continuing soviet pressure to lift 
us import restrictions on soviet furskins and other commodities 
and pressure for mostfavorednation mfn trade status which 
would give the soviet union preferential access to the us 
market he said 
under mfn the united states would grant the soviet union the 
same trading privileges that it offers most other foreign trading 
partners the mfn designation for the soviet union has been held up 
for years because of moscows restrictive emigration policies 
these issues are likely to persist in any trade negotiation 
between the soviet union and the united states hamby said 
currently negotiators are working on a successor to the fiveyear 
grain agreement between the soviet union and the united states 
