<TEXT>
the operator of the 53 billion shoreham 
nuclear plant was reported close to an agreement with the state 
thursday on a plan to abandon the power station without ever 
operating it commercially 
gov mario cuomo with the legislatures backing has been 
trying to scrap the plant because of arguments that long island 
could not be evacuated in a nuclear accident 
if the agreement is concluded shoreham will become the first 
completed nuclear power plant ever shut down without operating 
commercially the plant commissioned in 1973 took a decade to 
build and ran more than 10 times over budget 
sources speaking on condition of anonymity confirmed a report in 
the new york times on thursday that the plan would have the state 
take over the long island plant from its builder the long island 
lighting co then scrap it 
the utility would pay the estimated 500 million cost of the 
shutdown in return it would be guaranteed rate increases of 4 
percent to 5 percent a year for 10 years and would remain an 
independent investorowned utility 
the state had threatened a complete takeover of the utility to 
force a shutdown of shoreham 
cuomo confirmed that state and utility company representatives 
continued discussing the plants future he declined to say whether 
an agreement was at hand 
there are some areas important issues which we have agreed 
on there are still some critical issues that are unresolved 
said james lois a utility spokesman 
a source close to the talks said a sticking point was the issue 
of a change of the utilitys management which cuomo has said must 
be part of any settlement 
nora bredes a shoreham opponent and a member of the long island 
power authority said she was against a settlement with the long 
island lighting co 
from what ive heard of the proposed agreements long island 
will continue to be held hostage by lilco rates and the company 
walks away free and clear she said president reagan is 
offering noriega better terms 
