<TEXT>
on a recent sunday after a harlem congregation 
prayed for a mother who threw her baby out a window and the pastor 
preached against drug abuse a woman rose to advocate funding for 
the arts 
we have some real problems we have drugs we have housing 
problems we have a multitude of severe crises we have to face 
acknowledged mary schmidt campbell the citys cultural affairs 
commissioner 
why should we spend our time and our energy on culture 
what claim do we have on the citys resources she asked the 
flock of the abyssinian baptist church the citys oldest black 
house of worship the church made famous by the late adam clayton 
powell jr 
and then she answered her own question 
our culture she said has been our salvation 
in the six months since campbell succeeded bess myerson in one 
of the nations most powerful arts posts overseeing a cultural 
budget that is second only to the national endowment for the arts 
she has repeatedly argued for more arts money in a city where 
bridges are falling down crime is ever escalating and level 
untroubled ground is hard to find 
she has also restored the morale of a department dispirited by 
the scandal that forced myerson out of office and rekindled 
enthusiasm in the arts community 
campbell recalled the black heritage she and the congregation 
share music and art dating back to the days of slavery in the 
americas and before that to the great kingdoms and societies of 
africa 
when she mentioned the success of the dance theater of harlem 
and noted that 98 percent of the young singers in the boys choir of 
harlem go on to college the audience applauded vigorously 
later in an interview the commissioner said im really 
trying to accomplish a mentality an attitude about the arts that 
recognizes that it is one of the most essential services that the 
city provides to its citizens 
the real challenge for government is not to let itself get 
overwhelmed by its problems that is begin to seek out and carve 
out real resources for opportunity 
campbell 40 does not underestimate the difficulty of what she 
is trying to do when she became commissioner last october she had 
hopes of doubling the departments budget 
however two weeks after her appointment the stock market 
crashed mayor edward i koch recently proposed that the agency cut 
6 million from its current budget of 133 million for fiscal 1989 
campbell remains undaunted 
culture she says helps educate people who are going to be 
our leaders who we have to think of as being the salvation for the 
city and it helps in the reclamations of communities 
moreover artsrelated tourism is among the citys most important 
sources of revenue 
during myersons tenure the importance of culture as something 
that was not just a leisure time activity had not been 
conveyed said campbell quickly adding not that i was 
critical of her personally 
myerson a former miss america was a glamorous presence at gala 
cultural events and the publics interest in her put the 
relatively new and small department of cultural affairs in the 
spotlight 
the department is 11 years old it had been lumped in with the 
parks department and has about 55 employees 
this year the department provided 66 million to 32 major 
cultural institutions ranging from the metropolitan museum of art 
to el museo del barrio for operating and energy costs it also 
distributed 13 million to arts groups in grant money for programs 
or projects such as the metropolitan operas free performances in 
city parks 
i think bess was very concerned about bringing some visibility 
to the agency said kathleen hughes assistant commissioner for 
program services 
john hayworth assistant commissioner for cultural institutions 
agreed she brought an immediacy an understanding of the citys 
political life 
but the controversy surrounding myersons romantic involvement 
with millionaire carl andy capasso took its toll on the 
department she was accused of improperly influencing a judge 
presiding over his divorce case 
it has been a difficult time for people here hughes said 
i dont think theres any denying that going through something 
like what weve been through in terms of publicity has an effect 
campbell the daughter of a philadelphia family court judge 
received a doctorate in humanities at syracuse university where 
she wrote a study of the late american artist romare bearden 
as director of the studio museum of harlem for 10 years she 
transformed it from a struggling community arts project occupying 
two floors over a liquor store and fried chicken outlet into a 
premier fine arts museum focusing on black artists it has a 2 
million annual budget and is the only museum of its kind accredited 
by the american association of museums 
campbell also taught english literature for two years at nkumbi 
international college a school in zambia for refugees from south 
africa 
those in the arts mainstream are eager to praise her 
shes intelligent energetic and a compatible person said 
martin segal chairman emeritus of lincoln center for the 
performing arts and chairman of the board of the upcoming new york 
festival of the arts 
william h luers president of the metropolitan museum of art 
said hes dazzled by her intelligence 
one of the things that is difficult in government is to 
understand how museums work she has come from a museum environment 
and she knows the issues she knows the concerns the weaknesses 
the strengths he said 
campbell knows also that new york is the nations cultural 
capital and she is eager to exert new yorks influence on the 
national scene 
</TEXT>
