<TEXT>
mary deng once lived with her husband and 
five children in the relative comfort of a village in southern 
sudan today she lives in her nations capital in a shack without 
water or sanitation a refugee in her own country 
a 5yearold civil war in southern sudan chased the family away 
from their home along with an estimated 820000 other people 
forced from their homes into lives of poverty hunger and social 
ostracism 
mrs dengs story is similar to those of many of the others 
the army came into our village and took our cattle and killed 
many people she said 
my husband fled before me to get away from recruiters for both 
the army and the rebels i joined him with our five children 
later 
the dengs are among the estimated 400000 to 600000 southerners 
who have crowded into eight camps around khartoum 
they run in all directions mainly toward khartoum and sudans 
other cities to become wards of an impoverished state 
more than a quarter million have fled even into neighboring 
starving wartorn ethiopia several thousand of those died because 
they arrived after long treks too weak to be saved 
the refugees blame their plight on both sides in the war rebels 
and soldiers and the tribal and ethnic conflicts that are at the 
root of the fighting 
about 6 million people remain in the south where the population 
is mainly christian and animist of african extraction sixteen 
million arabdescended moslems live in the dominant north 
because of the great religious and ethnic divisions between 
north and south sudan has been torn by hostilities in the south 
for most of the 32 years since it asserted its independence from 
britain and egypt on jan 1 1956 
but for hundreds of years before that southern and northern 
tribes have fought over pastureland and water northerners 
traditionally dominating as they do now 
the current round of warfare began in the spring of 1983 
the rebel leader john garang is fighting for a greater share 
for the south of development money and of sudans potential wealth 
from petroleum and mineral reserves mostly in the south 
southern tribes like garangs dinka form the backbone of his 
sudan peoples liberation army spla 
the sudanese army recruited arab tribes and gave them modern 
weapons 
in 1985 the government started a policy of arming arab tribes 
to help in fighting the spla said sulaiman baldo a southerner 
who is a professor at the university of khartoum he told an 
interviewer the new automatic weapons enable arab tribes to 
dominate in intertribal clashes 
baldo recently coauthored a book on an alleged massacre a year 
ago by an arab tribe he wrote that more than 1000 dinkas were 
burned to death as police and soldiers watched without intervening 
the government denies the atrocity charges maintaining that the 
victims died in cross fires it also denies that it shirks its duty 
to displaced southerners 
we give them help but not just to anyone so that they dont 
become encouraged and come to stay and be fed for free and not 
work said elhag eltayeb sudans acting commissioner for 
relief and rehabilitation 
the southerners in the khartoum camps he added are people 
who used to be producers and are now just consumers they affect 
the citys already taxed infrastructure 
in the civil war itself the spla now controls most of the 
southern countryside with government troops in control of a 
handful of large towns diplomatic sources said 
the fighting nevertheless has forced southerners to flee their 
cultivated land and their cattle 
noncombatant southerners who have remained in the combat area 
also are in a bad way said a diplomatic source with access to 
military information 
the spla go on recruiting trips into villages and attack them 
if the villagers refuse to support them he said the army 
troops view most dinka youth as potential spla supporters 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

