<TEXT>
egypt built the aswan high dam two decades 
ago as a safeguard against the whims of the nile river but the 
worst drought in 70 years has dangerously lowered water levels and 
threatens to shut down the dams electricpower generators 
the government is using television jingles and newspaper 
campaigns to urge egyptians to conserve water and electricity 
president hosni mubarak warned on television that thousands of 
villages could go dark this summer unless the eightyearlong 
drought upriver eases 
he said the water of lake nasser the aswan dams 
1335squaremile reservoir is perilously close to a level 
impossible to sustain electricity generation 
the dam built during the 1960s with soviet help and inaugurated 
in 1971 was intended mainly to end annual killer floods it also 
was to provide adequate nile water to irrigate egypts agricultural 
heartland along its banks 
in addition it supplies 30 percent of egypts electricity 
experts say agricultural production has escaped serious harm so 
far but could be affected by another year of drought agriculture 
was the main casualty from the nile valleys last serious drought 
which began in 1913 and continued for seven years 
in the current drought the high dam has been credited with 
sparing egypt the famine that has spread across sudan and ethiopia 
upriver but the prolonged lack of rainfall at the ugandan and 
ethiopian headwaters of the white nile and blue nile has lowered 
the rivers level in egypt by more than 69 feet at the high dam 
the water surface is now 508 feet above sea level 
summer rains in ethiopia normally provide the nile with 84 
percent of its water 
this past january the month when the river is always at its 
shallowest houseboats were high and dry in cairo 600 miles 
downstream from aswan for the first time in anyones memory nile 
cruises from luxor 450 miles south of cairo to abu simbel were 
abandoned or started upstream from luxor 
transnile ferry service was halted at luxor for a while last 
year and longtime residents reported more land outcroppings in 
the niles dark murky water than ever before 
maher abaza the minister of electricity and energy sounded the 
alarm almost a year ago cautioning against increased consumption 
and waste of electricity and water 
consumption continued to climb however and official figures 
indicate that at least 45 percent of cairos share of the nile 
waters is wasted by negligence and the citys outmoded water system 
current predictions hold that the water level at the dam will 
decrease to 495 feet above sea level by july abaza said in a 
recent interview 
that will mean that the dam will be able to work only at half 
capacity producing 900 megawatts abaza said if the level 
goes under 147 meters 485 feet production of the high dam 
will be zero 
he added that generating plants are producing electricity as 
fast as they can now just to keep up with an everincreasing demand 
much of the increase in demand has been in the countryside 
where peasants returning from wellpaying jobs in saudi arabian oil 
regions have come home with electric fans ovens and television 
sets 
mubarak said in his tv address that if highdam generation 
stops the government will have to keep factories working by 
cutting off power to some of the countrys 5000 villages 
egypts 54 million people use 45 billion kilowatthours of 
electricity increasing by up to 20 percent a year figures 
indicate that the steady increase is due to what egyptians regard 
as luxury items such as air conditioners and color television sets 
egyptians open their taps and find water and switch on the 
light and everything lights up and they think that it is easy and 
will remain that way said abaza 
but they have to start cooperating and curbing their 
consumption or there are going to be serious consequences 
</TEXT>
