<DOCNO> AP880512-0266 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
koslov was stronger in his criticism of the secrecy i think 
it was handled very badly there was no reason why they couldnt 
have informed the embassy personnel early on the lesson 
learned is to treat your people as though they have some 
intelligence 
after the radiation problem became publicly known in 1976 the 
state department denied press reports including a story in the 
soviet government newspaper izvestia that the problem was 
exacerbated by radiofrequency and microwave emissions from us 
equipment 
but a dec 5 1975 cia memorandum dealing with the soviet beams 
said some embassy staff members probably have received much 
larger exposures of electromagnetic radiation due to leakage in 
coaxial cable shields for cables running through the embassy 
interior from transmitters to antennas this problem may not be 
limited to the embassy in moscow 
in other documents the cias donald myers also expressed 
concern over highfrequency radio radiation induced in telephone 
and other wiring leading into the ambassadors ninthfloor office 
due to spillover from a miniloop antenna mounted outside 
the antenna was subsequently moved to a different location on 
the embassy roof 
paul brodeur author of the zapping of america a book 
dealing with the moscow embassy affair and other cases of microwave 
exposure said he had been told by intelligence sources whom he 
declined to identify that there was always a question whether 
our own electronic countermeasures within the embassy were 
responsible for some of the irradiation of the employees 
a good many of the biologicalmedical problems at the embassy 
may well have been caused by our own efforts to jam the lowlevel 
incoming russian signals brodeur said 
the belated disclosure of the microwave bombardment prompted a 
series of administrative claims and lawsuits against the us 
government by employees and dependents who alleged that they had 
suffered health injuries because of exposure to the moscow beams 
to help defend itself against such legal actions the state 
department in 197678 funded a 1 million epidemiological study of 
moscow embassy personnel carried out under contract by the johns 
hopkins university school of hygiene and public health 
dr pollack the state department medical consultant said that 
without that hopkins study state would be sitting in the soup 
because there were about 250 million in tort actions on the books 
and every one of those has been withdrawn without a penny being 
paid 
there were about 100 someodd actions pollack said 
a virginia woman whose son was born with spina bifida a serious 
birth defect declined to comment in detail on the status of an 
administrative claim she brought against the state department in 
1977 
the woman who asked that her name not be used said regarding 
the possibility that her sons birth defect may have been linked to 
microwave exposure in moscow the only thing i can say is that 
its impossible to know theres no way well ever ever know 
thats the one thing i have learned 
another case involved a 175 million suit brought against the 
government on behalf of a boy born in 1973 with severe 
hydrocephalus a birth defect of the brain and central nervous 
system the boys father had served in moscow as a marine security 
guard 
peter a danelo a seattle attorney said the suit brought in 
federal court in los angeles alleged injury due to microwave 
radiation as well as medical malpractice at navy hospitals 
the microwave part of the suit was dismissed by the trial court 
the court cited what is known as the feres doctrine under which 
the federal government cannot be held liable for injuries suffered 
by activeduty military personnel or in this case for a childs 
physical injuries derived from his fathers activeduty injury 
danelo said the malpractice part of the case also proved 
unsuccessful 
h rowan gaither an official at the state departments office 
of the legal adviser said we had a group of moscow microwave 
files and they were all retired because they were not being 
actively pursued 
he said he was unable to confirm pollacks figures on the total 
number and dollar amount of the claims because the files have been 
sent to a federal records storage center in st louis 
the johns hopkins epidemiological study released in november 
1978 concluded that no convincing evidence was discovered that 
would directly implicate the exposure to microwave radiation by the 
employees at the moscow embassy in the causation of any adverse 
health effects as of the time of this analysis 
critics of the study however have voiced concern over the use 
of employees and dependents from us embassies and consulates in 
eastern europe as a control group for comparison to the health 
experience of moscow embassy personnel 
a confidential draft version of the study report itself noted 
that some of the members of the control group could have been 
exposed to microwave surveillance 
this was of concern especially since several participants in 
the study informed us that there indeed was surveillance using 
microwave technology at some of the comparison posts the draft 
document said 
this section was deleted in the final version of the report 
according to the minutes of an oct 17 1978 meeting of dr pollack 
with members of the study staff it was deleted because it was 
really heresay 
at the recommendation of the health study team the state 
department contracted with the johns hopkins applied physics 
laboratory for preparation of a retrospective technical analysis of 
the complex microwave radiation fields monitored within the moscow 
embassy 
the findings of this technical analysis were evaluated by the 
electromagnetic radiation management advisory council known as 
ermac a nowdefunct scientific panel that operated under the aegis 
of the commerce departments national telecommunications and 
information administration 
in june 1981 a report issued by ntia said the 14member 
advisory panel agreed that there is no scientific evidence nor 
are there any theoretical grounds to suggest that biological 
effects would be expected to occur from the type and low levels of 
exposure presented consequently ermac concluded that no 
deleterious biological effects to personnel would be anticipated 
from the microwave exposures at the us embassy in moscow 
however several experts on nonionizing radiation say they 
believe the state department and ermac may well have jumped to 
scientifically unwarranted conclusions in seeking to rule out 
possible health effects on personnel exposed to the moscow 
radiation 
among them is the university of michigans steneck who cited a 
variety of studies that have been done over the past few years 
since the 197678 johns hopkins epidemiological survey finding 
significant effects at very low radiation power levels 
i can see no reason why i would rest easier today than i would 
have 10 years ago he said as we learn more and more 
about the ways in which this radiation can interact with the body 
we find that there are more subtle ways than we initially 
suspected 
</TEXT>
