the 18 billion in wholeherd buyout payments for example about 
38 percent was provided by assessments 
but lyng has been steadfast in opposing another buyout or 
diversion program federation leaders say therefore dairy farmers 
are being asked to put pressure on members of congress as well as 
on lyng to avoid the next 50cent cut in supports 
one of the arguments used by the federation is that part of the 
recent slide in dairy supports has been accompanied by an easing of 
production costs mainly lower feed prices but now with grain 
exports and the economy rebounding costs are going up again 
thus the federation says it makes sense to put brakes on the 
slide in milk supports or else see thousands of dairy farmers hurt 
economically 
according to usda economists the price of manufacturing 
milk used to make butter cheese and other products averaged 1227 
per hundredweight in the first three months of 1988 down 63 cents 
from a year ago 
