<TEXT>
continental airlines has entered into an 
agreement with kansas officials under which the airline will credit 
millions of miles to members of its airlines frequent flier club 
attorney general robert t stephan said thursday 
stephan said that as recently as may 3 continental advertised 
minimum credits of at least 1000 miles per flight segment while it 
had been making minimum entries of only 750 miles since jan 1 
members of frequent flier clubs accumulate mileage credits that 
can be used for free or reduced fare airplane tickets 
besides the mileage credit discrepancy continental advertised 
that members of its onepass club could receive frequent flier 
award travel to tokyo but the airline did not make such trips 
available stephan charged 
stephan said the brochures and inflight magazine advertisements 
were deceptive he said the company attempted to save millions of 
dollars worth of award travel tickets nationwide 
in the agreement it signed with stephans office continental 
denied it violated kansas consumer protection laws although it 
agreed to pay 20000 in costs and investigation fees 
the houstonbased airline said that when it announced its triple 
mileage program in a jan 21 letter to onepass members it clearly 
stated the mileage minimum being tripled was 750 miles the company 
also said a march 1988 brochure used the 750mile figure 
continental said in the agreement it depicted tokyo as a 
frequent flier award destination because members wishing to go 
there could earn credits to make that trip by flying on sister 
airline air micronesia 
the airline agreed to credit onepass members at the 1000mile 
rate retroactively and keep the 1000mile rate in effect through 
july 
it also agreed to withdraw any remaining advertisements and 
brochures using the 1000mile figure the airline said it would 
add tokyo as an award travel destination through dec 31 
stephan estimated there are more than 2 million active onepass 
members during the first 16 weeks of 1988 continental enrolled an 
average of more than 45000 members a week he said 
